Thank you for your noticings, wondering, and headline.  
These graphs are only a model for transmission.  There are many more variables and assumptions that need to be made to predict the effect of coronavirus.  You may want to read the website Fivethirtyeight article “Why It’s So Freaking Hard to Make a Good COVID-19 Model (https://tinyurl.com/C19Model).  There, you will read about some of the dozens of assumptions that need to be made to determine the transmission rate and the fatality rate.

@Ruby A. 
Thank you as always for your response.  Take another look at the two graphs.  They are simplified models in which it is assumed that people only transmit the infection to two people.  Which graph models social distancing? Which infected person uses social distancing?  
In Friday’s Reveal, you’ll see a few other scenarios.  Using only 3 stages of transmission, rather than 6, you can calculate the effect of social distancing for different scenarios.  It’s very revealing!

